    { q: "Can you explain the gearing effect in a residual appraisal and why it matters for risk assessment?", a: "The residual land value is the difference between two large numbers (GDV and total costs). Because land value is a relatively small proportion of GDV, even modest percentage changes in revenue or costs translate into disproportionately large percentage changes in land value. For example, a 10% fall in GDV on a scheme where land is 25% of GDV could reduce the residual by 40% or more. This means residual appraisals carry inherent uncertainty, and any professional advice must be accompanied by sensitivity analysis to quantify the range of possible outcomes." },
    { q: "How would you set up a sensitivity analysis for a mixed-use development appraisal, and which variables would you prioritise?", a: "I would construct a two-variable sensitivity matrix in Argus Developer or Excel, with GDV variation on one axis and build cost variation on the other, typically in 2.5% or 5% increments from -10% to +10%. For a mixed-use scheme, I would also separately test the residential sales rate (absorption), commercial yield, and construction programme length, as delays compound finance costs. Priority variables are those with the greatest uncertainty: in the current market, sales values and construction cost inflation are usually the two most volatile inputs. I would highlight the 'crossover point' where profit falls below the funder's minimum threshold — typically 15–20% profit on GDV for residential." },
    { q: "What is Monte Carlo simulation and when would you recommend it over standard sensitivity analysis?", a: "Monte Carlo simulation is a probabilistic technique that assigns statistical distributions (e.g., triangular, PERT, normal) to key appraisal inputs and runs thousands of randomised iterations to generate a probability distribution of the output. I would recommend it for large-scale or complex schemes where the client or funder needs to understand the probability of achieving target returns — for example, a build-to-rent scheme with 500+ units and a 5-year delivery programme. It goes beyond sensitivity analysis by quantifying likelihood rather than just showing discrete what-if scenarios. It is particularly useful for investment committee presentations and loan covenant modelling." },
    { q: "In a planning viability assessment, how do you ensure your sensitivity analysis meets RICS and NPPF requirements?", a: "Under RICS Financial Viability in Planning guidance and PPG Viability, the appraisal must be transparent and the inputs evidence-based. I present a base case using benchmark land value (EUV+ or AUV), then provide a sensitivity table testing GDV and build cost variations to demonstrate the range within which the scheme can support affordable housing and S106/CIL obligations. I cross-reference inputs to BCIS for costs and comparable evidence for values. I ensure the methodology aligns with the Harman Guidance approach and present results clearly so that planning officers can understand the impact of, say, increasing affordable housing from 20% to 35% on scheme viability. All assumptions are disclosed in accordance with Red Book requirements." },
    { q: "How would you explain to a non-technical planning committee why a 5% fall in house prices could make a developer's viability case valid?", a: "I would explain that development is like a see-saw: on one side you have the sale price of the homes, and on the other you have all the costs — building, land, fees, and contributions to infrastructure and affordable housing. The developer's land payment sits in the middle as the balancing point. Because the land price is worked out as the leftover after all costs, even a small drop in house prices — say 5% — takes a much bigger bite out of that leftover. In pound terms, a 5% drop on a £20m scheme is £1m off the top, but if the land value was only £3m, that's a third of the land budget gone. This means the scheme can no longer afford the same level of affordable housing or S106 contributions and remain commercially viable. I would show the committee a simple table illustrating these numbers." }
